    stem: "A 65-year-old male with a VP (ventriculoperitoneal) shunt for normal pressure hydrocephalus presents to the ED with headache, nausea, vomiting, and drowsiness. These symptoms have been worsening over 2 days. CT head shows enlarged ventricles compared to his prior imaging. What does this presentation most likely represent?",
    options: ["Migraine headache unrelated to the shunt", "VP shunt malfunction causing recurrent hydrocephalus", "Normal pressure hydrocephalus progression despite functioning shunt", "Viral gastroenteritis causing the nausea and vomiting"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    rationaleLong: "This patient presents with signs of recurrent hydrocephalus from VP shunt malfunction. VP shunts are devices that drain excess CSF from the brain's ventricles to the peritoneal cavity through a subcutaneous catheter system with a one-way valve. Shunt malfunction can result from obstruction (proximal or distal catheter blockage), disconnection, migration, infection, or valve failure. The clinical presentation of shunt malfunction mirrors the symptoms of the original hydrocephalus: (1) Headache - from increased ICP; typically worse in the morning or when lying down; (2) Nausea and vomiting - from increased ICP stimulating the vomiting center in the brainstem; (3) Drowsiness/lethargy - from cerebral compression; (4) CT showing enlarged ventricles compared to baseline - this is the key diagnostic finding. Comparison with prior imaging is essential, as some patients with treated hydrocephalus have ventricles that appear larger than normal but are stable at their baseline. The emergency nurse should: (1) Compare current CT with the most recent prior imaging to assess for interval ventricular enlargement; (2) Assess the shunt hardware - palpate the shunt reservoir (if accessible) for pump function; (3) Obtain a shunt series (skull, chest, and abdominal X-rays) to evaluate catheter continuity, position, and disconnection; (4) Check for signs of shunt infection (fever, erythema along the shunt tract, abdominal tenderness at the distal tip); (5) Notify neurosurgery for shunt evaluation and possible revision; (6) Monitor neurological status closely for signs of herniation. The patient may need emergent shunt revision or, as a temporizing measure, tapping of the shunt reservoir to drain CSF and relieve ICP.",
    learningObjective: "Recognize VP shunt malfunction presenting with recurrent hydrocephalus symptoms and enlarged ventricles on CT",
    blueprintCategory: "Neurological Emergencies",
    subtopic: "Increased ICP Management",
    difficulty: 3,
    cognitiveLevel: "analysis",
    questionType: "MCQ_SINGLE",
    examTrap: "Always compare current CT with prior baseline imaging in shunt patients - ventricles may appear 'large' but be stable at the patient's baseline",
    clinicalPearls: ["Shunt malfunction symptoms mirror original hydrocephalus: headache, N/V, drowsiness", "Compare CT with prior imaging for interval ventricular change", "Shunt series (skull/chest/abdomen XR) evaluates catheter integrity", "Palpate shunt reservoir to assess pump function"],
    safetyNote: "Shunt malfunction can progress to herniation - maintain close neurological monitoring and have neurosurgery on standby",
    distractorRationales: ["Headache with enlarged ventricles in a shunt patient is not a migraine", "Enlarging ventricles despite shunt indicate malfunction, not disease progression with functioning shunt", "The combination of neurological symptoms with enlarged ventricles points to shunt failure, not gastroenteritis"],
    lessonLink: "/emergency/lessons/increased-icp"
