    stem: "A 35-year-old male presents to the ED following a generalized tonic-clonic seizure. He is post-ictal with GCS 11. His blood glucose is 98 mg/dL. A friend reports the patient uses cocaine and had been binge drinking for 3 days, stopping abruptly yesterday. The patient's last drink was approximately 36 hours ago. What is the most likely cause of this seizure?",
    options: ["Primary epilepsy", "Alcohol withdrawal seizure", "Cocaine-induced seizure from acute intoxication", "Hyponatremia from beer potomania"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    rationaleLong: "The timing of this seizure - approximately 36 hours after the last alcoholic drink following a 3-day binge - is classic for alcohol withdrawal seizures. Alcohol withdrawal seizures typically occur 6-48 hours after the last drink, with peak incidence at 24-48 hours. They are generalized tonic-clonic in nature, often occurring in clusters (2-6 seizures), and are a manifestation of CNS hyperexcitability from sudden removal of alcohol's inhibitory effect on GABA receptors and potentiation of excitatory NMDA glutamate receptors. The timeline of alcohol withdrawal follows a predictable pattern: (1) 6-24 hours: minor withdrawal symptoms (anxiety, tremor, insomnia, nausea, tachycardia); (2) 12-48 hours: alcoholic hallucinosis (visual, auditory, or tactile hallucinations with intact sensorium); (3) 6-48 hours: withdrawal seizures (peak 24-48 hours); (4) 48-96 hours: delirium tremens (DT) - severe withdrawal with confusion, agitation, autonomic instability, hallucinations, and potential death (5-15% mortality if untreated). Alcohol withdrawal seizures are a warning sign that the patient may progress to delirium tremens, and prophylactic treatment with benzodiazepines should be initiated. The CIWA-Ar (Clinical Institute Withdrawal Assessment for Alcohol-Revised) protocol can guide benzodiazepine dosing. While cocaine can cause seizures, cocaine-induced seizures occur during acute intoxication (not 36 hours later). The friend's history confirms the binge drinking pattern and abrupt cessation, making alcohol withdrawal the most likely etiology. The emergency nurse should administer benzodiazepines (lorazepam or diazepam) per CIWA protocol, monitor for signs of DT progression, replete thiamine before glucose, and check magnesium and electrolytes.",
    learningObjective: "Identify the timeline of alcohol withdrawal seizures (6-48 hours post-cessation) and recognize them as a warning for potential delirium tremens",
    blueprintCategory: "Neurological Emergencies",
    subtopic: "Seizure Management and Status Epilepticus",
    difficulty: 3,
    cognitiveLevel: "analysis",
    questionType: "MCQ_SINGLE",
    examTrap: "Alcohol withdrawal seizures peak at 24-48 hours. DT peaks at 48-96 hours. Withdrawal seizures warn that DT may follow",
    clinicalPearls: ["Alcohol withdrawal seizures: 6-48 hours after last drink (peak 24-48)", "Delirium tremens: 48-96 hours (5-15% mortality if untreated)", "Withdrawal seizures can progress to DT - initiate benzodiazepine prophylaxis", "Give thiamine BEFORE glucose in all alcohol-dependent patients"],
    safetyNote: "Alcohol withdrawal seizures are a medical emergency and warning sign for DT - always admit for monitoring and benzodiazepine protocol",
    distractorRationales: ["Primary epilepsy does not explain the temporal relationship with alcohol cessation", "Cocaine seizures occur during acute intoxication, not 36 hours later", "Hyponatremia from beer potomania would show abnormal sodium levels"],
