  {
    stem: "A 58-year-old male is being evaluated in the ED for acute ischemic stroke. His NIHSS score is 22, indicating a severe stroke. CT angiography shows a left internal carotid artery (ICA) terminus occlusion. He received IV tPA 20 minutes ago. Why is mechanical thrombectomy particularly important for this patient despite receiving tPA?",
    options: ["tPA is sufficient for all stroke types and thrombectomy adds no benefit", "ICA terminus occlusions have an extremely low recanalization rate with tPA alone (approximately 4-8%), making mechanical thrombectomy essential for any chance of meaningful recovery", "Thrombectomy is only performed when tPA is contraindicated", "tPA should be stopped before thrombectomy can be performed"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    rationaleLong: "Large vessel occlusions (LVOs), particularly ICA terminus occlusions, have extremely low recanalization rates with IV tPA alone. The ICA terminus is where the internal carotid artery bifurcates into the anterior cerebral artery (ACA) and middle cerebral artery (MCA), and occlusion at this location produces a massive stroke affecting a large territory of the brain. Studies show that IV tPA recanalizes ICA terminus occlusions in only approximately 4-8% of cases, compared to approximately 30% for distal MCA occlusions. The larger the clot burden, the less effective tPA becomes because the drug cannot penetrate and dissolve the entire thrombus. Mechanical thrombectomy using stent retrievers or aspiration devices achieves recanalization rates of 80-90% in large vessel occlusions, representing a dramatic improvement over tPA alone. The landmark thrombectomy trials (MR CLEAN, ESCAPE, EXTEND-IA, SWIFT PRIME, REVASCAT) demonstrated that thrombectomy significantly improves functional outcomes when added to IV tPA for anterior circulation LVO strokes. Important points: (1) tPA should NOT be stopped or delayed while arranging thrombectomy - it provides some chance of early reperfusion and may reduce clot burden even if it doesn't fully recanalize; (2) The 'drip and ship' model (administer tPA at the presenting hospital and transfer to a thrombectomy-capable center) is the standard approach for patients presenting to non-comprehensive stroke centers; (3) Thrombectomy provides benefit even when performed after tPA; (4) Direct thrombectomy without tPA may be appropriate in specific situations (e.g., DOAC use, recent surgery). The NIHSS of 22 confirms a severe stroke that correlates with a large territory at risk and supports the need for aggressive reperfusion therapy.",
    learningObjective: "Understand why mechanical thrombectomy is essential for large vessel occlusions where tPA alone has minimal recanalization rates",
    blueprintCategory: "Neurological Emergencies",
    subtopic: "Ischemic vs Hemorrhagic Stroke",
    difficulty: 4,
    cognitiveLevel: "analysis",
    questionType: "MCQ_SINGLE",
    examTrap: "tPA recanalizes ICA terminus occlusions in only 4-8%. Thrombectomy achieves 80-90%. Both should be given when eligible (bridging therapy)",
    clinicalPearls: ["ICA terminus occlusion: tPA recanalization rate ~4-8%", "Thrombectomy recanalization rate: 80-90% for LVO", "Do NOT stop tPA while arranging thrombectomy - bridging therapy is standard", "NIHSS >=6 with LVO = strong thrombectomy candidate"],
    safetyNote: "Time is brain - facilitate the fastest possible transfer to a thrombectomy-capable center. Every 30-minute delay reduces the chance of good outcome",
    distractorRationales: ["tPA alone is insufficient for LVO - recanalization rates are very low", "Thrombectomy is performed in addition to tPA, not only when tPA is contraindicated", "tPA should continue while thrombectomy is being arranged"],
    lessonLink: "/emergency/lessons/stroke-recognition"
  }
